title: import_graph_def's input_map doesn't remap control inputs
body:
If a graph `g` has a node `y` with a control input like `^x`, I would have thought that `tf.import_graph_def(g, input_map={"x": z})` would result in a graph having a node `y` with a control input`^z`. 

Instead I get an error: `ValueError: Attempted to map inputs that were not found in graph_def: [x:0]`.  This is on master.

Complete example: 

```python
import tensorflow as tf
g1=tf.Graph()
with g1.as_default():
    x=tf.constant(0.0, name="x")
    with tf.control_dependencies([x]):
        y=tf.constant(1, name="y")
g2=tf.Graph()
with g2.as_default():
    z=tf.constant(1.0, name="z")
    tf.import_graph_def(g1.as_graph_def(), input_map={"x": z})

```
comments:
Nice reproducible example!

It works if you do `^x` instead of `x`

`    tf.import_graph_def(g1.as_graph_def(), input_map={"^x": z})
`

Looking at the relevant logic, in importer.py, it seems it takes name of node directly from graphdef, so "x" would have two names, "x" and "^x" depending on the role, and you'd need to specify two remapping rules for it. Not ideal, not sure if there's an easy way to fix it, cc @mrry because he left a comment there 

      for i, input_name in enumerate(
          [_CanonicalInputName(x) for x in node.input]):

Thanks! Unfortunately, if you use the C API via `TF_GraphImportGraphDefWithReturnOutputs` in analogy to the above example, it still doesn't work to use `^x` instead of `x` as the remapping key. 

AFAICT, mapping control inputs is impossible in the C API.

Reassigning this to @skye, who's currently reconciling the Python and C APIs for importing graphs.

(If the trick @yaroslavvb suggested works, that's only by accident, since we didn't originally intend to provide a way to remap control inputs using `tf.import_graph_def()`. It doesn't seem too problematic to allow it though...)

As @yaroslavvb noted, you should use "^x" in the input map. Using "x" in the input map is equivalent to "x:0", i.e. the non-control output of `x`.

However, when I try running your code snippet above with "^x", it looks like that functionality is broken. I'll work on patching it.

@malmaud, the C API should work with control inputs. You'd use something like the following:
`TF_ImportGraphDefOptionsAddInputMapping(opts, "x", -1, {z, -1})`

Note the use of -1 to indicate a control edge. This should be documented in the header comment, sorry for the confusion. For those following along, this functionality is only checked in on master (not 1.0).
Thanks! I did eventually figure out the `-1` magic constant and wrote [a PR](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/7724) to document it.
It has been 14 days with no activity and this issue has an assignee.Please update the label and/or status accordingly.
It has been 14 days with no activity and this issue has an assignee.Please update the label and/or status accordingly.
A member of the TensorFlow organization has replied after the stat:awaiting tensorflower label was applied.
Nagging Assignee: It has been 14 days with no activity and this issue has an assignee. Please update the label and/or status accordingly.
@skye any updates on the patch?

Oops, forgot to update this issue.

This has been resolved. To remap a control input, use the `F_ImportGraphDefOptionsRemapControlDependency` method: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/c/c_api.h#L922

The -1 trick should still work too, although I think is technically undefined behavior.

title: How change the package name of tensorflow android camera demo
body: I have built two Android demo with two different custom models. However in order to install both apps on my device I need to change the name of one of these. Is there an easy way to change the name of the apk file?
comments: You can change the Android package in [AndroidManifest.xml](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/examples/android/AndroidManifest.xml#L19) and [BUILD](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/examples/android/BUILD#L71) to avoid the conflict.

I installed TensorFlow version 1.0.0-rc2 on Windows 7 SP1 x64 Ultimate (Python 3.5.2 |Anaconda custom (64-bit)) using:

    pip install --upgrade https://storage.googleapis.com/tensorflow/windows/cpu/tensorflow-1.0.0rc2-cp35-cp35m-win_amd64.whl

When I try running the test script from https://web.archive.org/web/20170214034751/https://www.tensorflow.org/get_started/os_setup#test_the_tensorflow_installation in Eclipse 4.5 or in the console:

    import tensorflow as tf
    print('TensorFlow version: {0}'.format(tf.__version__))
    hello = tf.constant('Hello, TensorFlow!')
    sess = tf.Session()
    print(sess.run(hello))

title: Import Tensorflow lib with Qt for Android
body:
I tried to import tensorflow lib into my Qt project, the build procedure was followed as described in contrib/makefile

I somehow managed with Desktop and iOS platforms, but failed with Android with linking problem:
```
/Users/chen/Documents/Git/tensorflow/tensorflow/contrib/makefile/gen_android/protobuf/lib/libprotobuf.a(strutil.o):strutil.cc:function google::protobuf::safe_strtof(char const*, float*): error: undefined reference to 'strtof'

Error while building/deploying project CrossDemo (kit: Android for armeabi-v7a (GCC 4.9, Qt 5.8.0))

OS: macOS 10.12.3
SDK: android-21
NDK: r13b
comments: @petewarden, could you take a quick look?
Are you compiling with --std=c++11? It looks like strtof was only enabled then.

Yes, sure.
I tried explicitly add c++11 configuration, which lead to the CXXFLAG as the following:

```
CXXFLAGS      = -fstack-protector-strong -DANDROID -march=armv7-a -mfloat-abi=softfp -mfpu=vfp -fno-builtin-memmove --sysroot=/Users/chen/Library/Android/android-ndk-r13b/platforms/android-16/arch-arm/ -std=c++11 -fno-rtti -fno-exceptions -fpic -O2 -mfpu=neon -DTF_LEAN_BINARY -DGOOGLE_PROTOBUF_NO_RTTI -DGOOGLE_PROTOBUF_NO_STATIC_INITIALIZER -g -g -marm -O0 -std=gnu++11 -Wall -W -D_REENTRANT -fPIC $(DEFINES)
```

I also explicitly add the libc.a/libc.so lib into my LIBS, as the following:

```
LIBS += -L/Users/chen/Library/Android/android-ndk-r13b/platforms/android-21/arch-arm64/usr/lib/libc.a
```

Still does not work, and encounter the link error as the following:

```
/Users/chen/Documents/Git/tensorflow/tensorflow/contrib/makefile/gen_android/lib/libtensorflow-core.a(net.o):net.cc:function tensorflow::internal::PickUnusedPortOrDie(): error: undefined reference to 'rand'
/Users/chen/Documents/Git/tensorflow/tensorflow/contrib/makefile/gen_android/lib/libtensorflow-core.a(subprocess.o):subprocess.cc:function tensorflow::SubProcess::Communicate(std::string const*, std::string*, std::string*) [clone .part.5]: error: undefined reference to 'sigemptyset'

Use NDK r10e mysteriously solved the problem.
r12b is the suggested NDK to use currently. There may be problems with arm64 builds produced by r10e.

Whoa. It looks like Java is having problems interoperating with Windows NT LAN Manager. I'm not sure if there's much Bazel or TensorFlow can do to help you unfortunately. It might be actionable in the sense that we could have done a better job reporting this error. I'll give it some thought and possibly send a patch to Bazel. But aside from that, I hope you don't mind if I close this one out. I'll reopen provided new information.

I solved this problem by using a CNTLM proxy and setting `http_proxy` and `https_proxy` like `http://127.0.0.1:3128`.

One strange thing is that `bazel` issued a warning saying that it ignores `http_proxy` while in fact not.

If you also experience certificate errors, find your `cacerts` file and insert the required certificate extracted using a browser or a similar tool.
Can you copy-paste the error message you're getting about it ignoring http_proxy?

Here is the output. The first thing is that warning. @kchodorow 

But I have to repeat that it is in fact using the proxy information in `http_proxy`. Normally, our network restricts any connection to the external networks, only through HTTP(S) proxies.

```
user@hostname:~/tensorflow-1.1.0$ bazel fetch "//tensorflow/... -//tensorflow/contrib/nccl/... -//tensorflow/examples/android/..."
Warning: ignoring http_proxy in environment.
.........
INFO: Downloading http://bazel-mirror.storage.googleapis.com/github.com/google/protobuf/archive/2b7430d96aeff2bb624c8d52182ff5e4b9f7f18a.tar.gz: 626,737 bytes

```

Ah, yeah, that warning is from the Bazel client. `http_proxy` is unset because otherwise it could interfere with the gRPC connection Bazel's about to make to its server.  The server (which actually runs the build) still uses `http_proxy`.

It's harmless, but if you wanted to avoid it you could set `HTTP_PROXY` instead, the client only checks for `http_proxy`.
That sounds like a system issue and not a Bazel issue. You might have better luck with Stack Overflow.

I had been stuck in the same issue and found the solution. It seems that the Openjdk JVM wans't able to make some types of http requests. I purged it and installed the Oracle JVM and was able to successfully build tensorflow. I also had to purge the Cuda installation but it was simple to install it back because the files were already in cache.

So, to fix this:
1. purge Cuda, OpenJDK and Bazel
2. Install Java JDK from [here](http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jdk9-downloads-3848520.html)
3. Reinstall Bazel, Cuda and CudNN
4. Run `./configure` again at tensorflow folder
5. Run the `bazel build`. This time it should work

My reason is https certificate always wrong when download https zip in WORKSPACE. I try to keytool import cert, it had no effect. Also because I do not how to configure cert when my company use a proxy to Internet.
Finally, I download all http/https zip by WGET with --no-check-cert(not precise), then install Apache server and modify http/https link to my Apache server url, bazel build success!!!
@ldrmcml what you said is just a workaround.

For me, maybe It is key problem to solve a https cert when there is a proxy web gateway.

bazel build -c opt  tensorflow/examples/android:tensorflow_native_libs --crosstool_top=//external:android/crosstool --cpu=armeabi-v7a  --host_crosstool_top=@bazel_tools//tools/cpp:toolchain
''

which works for me!

- https://stackoverflow.com/a/30699960

Run:

```sh
sudo /var/lib/dpkg/info/ca-certificates-java.postinst configure

Thanks @jart. I had found that one already and it wasn't the case, but it surely could have been. 

For the lost souls that end up here, the reason why this was happening is that I (wrongly) assumed that the Bazel repo for `apt` would work just fine for Ubuntu 18.04, but it did not (and severly, too). In fact, installing `bazel` that way overwrote some critical paths of the `openjdk-8-jre` or `oracle-java8-installer` installations, leaving basic functionalities such as `keytool` unaccessible. The fix was to remove bazel, uninstall / reinstally java, and simply use the recommended installer from Bazel's website, which does not raise these issues. Also, if you don't use Bazel for anything else, I would recommend installing it locally your home folder and with its own `openjdk` install, which reduces all the java mess to a bare minimum.

comments: @fchollet, could you take a quick look. @zero2hero2020, could you try it with the non-tensorflow backend perhaps?

It looks like axis is expecting a tensor, and it is getting a literal 1. Maybe try `axis=np.array(1)`?

```python
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import LSTM, BatchNormalization, Dense

seq = Sequential()
seq.add(LSTM(256,
        input_shape=(30, 512),
        activation='tanh',
        return_sequences=True))

    axis=1))

Hi zero2hero2020,

I cannot reproduce your issue. But here's what you can do:

1) I recommend that you use the following more modern model definition style:

```python
import keras

inputs = keras.layers.Input(shape=(30, 512))
x = keras.layers.LSTM(256, return_sequences=True)(inputs)
x = keras.layers.BatchNormalization(axis=1)(x)
x = keras.layers.LSTM(32)(x)
outputs = keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)
```

2) I recommend that you install and use the Keras 2 API, available via the `keras-2` branch of the Keras repo: https://github.com/fchollet/keras/tree/keras-2

Hi, sorry for the delay. I thought I'd have time to look at this but apparently I do not! @martinwicke do you know who can look this? (This = a checkpoint from 1.0 can't be loaded from 1.3, for more details start reading here: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/7490#issuecomment-332373089)

This is not super surprising -- I think the bidirectional rnn code that was used to write this checkpoint was in contrib at 1.0, and the internal structure of that code has changed since, changing some variable names, and thus making the checkpoint unreadable.

@ebrevdo can you confirm or refute this? The only thing that makes me wonder about the errors is that it's complaining about Adam state, but I still blame a scope name change for now.

We have a tool to help rewrite old checkpoints [here](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/contrib/rnn/python/tools/checkpoint_convert.py).  The top of the script has instructions on how to convert your old RNN checkpoints to a format that will work with TF 1.3+.
Let me know if this does not work. I'll close the issue for now.

title: how to use baidu wrap-ctc on tensorflow?
body:
when i use tensorflow ctc, i find it is very slow,,,
so i want use baidu wrap-ctc on tensorflow,

but how to write code?

when i use tensorflow ctc, i write it:
    print logits.get_shape()
    logits = tf.reshape(logits, [batch_size, -1, nout])
    logits = tf.transpose(logits, (1, 0, 2))
    print 'logits shape is '
    print logits.get_shape()
    labels = tf.SparseTensor(indices=label_idx, values=label_vals, shape=label_shape)
    print 'init label'
    loss = ctc_ops.ctc_loss(inputs=logits, labels=labels, sequence_length=seq_len)
    print 'init loss'
    cost = tf.reduce_mean(loss)
    print 'init cost'
    decoded, log_prob = ctc_ops.ctc_greedy_decoder(logits, seq_len)
    print 'init decoded'
    ler = tf.reduce_mean(tf.edit_distance(tf.cast(decoded[0], tf.int32),
                                          labels))
    print 'init ler'
comments: can you file this issue with maintainers of baidu ctc?

title: Fix dynamic_stitch gradient implementation
body:
This modifies the gradient calculation for the `dynamic_stitch` op so that it gives the correct gradient when the input indices have duplicate values (issue is described in more detail in #7397).

I also expanded the unit tests so that the gradient calculation is tested with a wider range of inputs (since it is now more complicated/error-prone), and added a test specifically for the duplicate indices case.
comments: Can one of the admins verify this patch?
Actually, hold off on reviewing this; I had an idea last night for a different implementation that might be more efficient.
The new implementation does seem to be an improvement.  I left both up there in case there are some internal benchmarks you want to run.

It looks like your implementation does `n-1` dynamic stitches if there are n inputs.  It seems like this could be reduce to a single dynamic stitch by dynamically stitching from constant tensors 0, 1, ... to get a `source` tensor that says where each destination came from.  This source tensor could then be used to mask out the inputs.  If that makes sense, could you see how it compares speed-wise?

Also, please rewrite the gradient tests to use `tf.test.compute_gradient_error`.  Comparing against numerical gradients avoids more possibilities for error, so it's good to do it unless there's a compelling reason.
Do you want me to change the existing tests in `testHigherRank` to use `compute_gradient_error` as well?
@drasmuss Nah, just yours is fine (unless you feel inspired).
@drasmuss Can you actually squash this time to make it easier to read?  The commits say "squash!" but are not squashed, which is confusing.

I did some speed tests, and it seems like implementation 2 (with the `n-1` `dynamic_stitches`) is the fastest.  That kind of surprised me, but I guess the masking operation is more expensive than the dynamic stitching.  Exactly where that tradeoff lies will probably depend on the size of the gradient versus the number of inputs.  But in general I think we expect the number of inputs to be fairly small, so the implementation 2 approach scales fairly well.

Let me know if that sounds good, and I'll squash them all and just keep implementation 2.
@drasmuss Could I see the numbers from the speed tests?  What was `n`?  Do you have a speed comparison with the (incorrect) baseline?

It is also be possible to massively accelerate the third implementation by writing a new C++ op that does

    merged[indices[m][i, ..., j], ...] = m

It would be pretty easy to make this by copying the current `DynamicStitchOp` kernel and (essentially) constant folding.

Also: Thank you for working on this!  I realize I'm asking for a lot, but it's important to minimize performance regressions to existing functionality.

Here's the quick script I put together to test things out, if you want to play with the numbers.  I didn't do any rigorous parameter sweeps.
``` python
import time

import numpy as np
import tensorflow as tf

stitch_size = 1000
n_inputs = 10
input_shape = (100, 50, 50)
reps = 10

with tf.device("/cpu:0"):
    idxs = [tf.constant(np.random.randint(stitch_size, size=input_shape[0]))
            for _ in range(n_inputs)]
    vals = [tf.constant(np.random.uniform(-1, 1, size=input_shape))
            for _ in range(n_inputs)]
    y = tf.dynamic_stitch(idxs, vals)
    grad = tf.gradients(y, vals)

total_time = 0.0
for _ in range(reps):
    with tf.Session() as sess:
        start = time.time()
        sess.run(grad)
        total_time += time.time() - start

print(total_time / reps)
```
on my computer this gives
```
baseline: 0.17385516166687012
implementation 1: 0.45461173057556153
implementation 2: 0.3225952863693237
implementation 3: 0.4177032709121704
```

I think a 2x slowdown is too frightening without doing some more work to reduce, since dynamic_stitch shows up in the embedding layers of a lot of models.  Would you be interested in trying the new C++ op to see if that reduces the gap?  I'm afraid it wouldn't reduce it all that much, though, since as is the gradients are very simple.

@ebrevdo Do you have any thoughts here?  I think the embedding usage of dynamic stitch doesn't have this problem since the indices are all unique there.  Unfortunately, the op doesn't know that.

One option would be to just change the definition of `dynamic_stitch` to not allow duplicate indices, since that is how it seems to be used a lot of the time.

However, one of the important uses of `dynamic_stitch` (from my perspective anyway) is that it's the only way I can find to do sparse updates on tensors that both runs on the GPU and has a gradient implementation (as suggested by @yaroslavvb here http://stackoverflow.com/questions/37061808/how-does-tensorflow-indexing-work). And that use case would be made less efficient if we don't allow duplicate indices (for the same reason that the gradient is less efficient here, since we'd need to manually compute the non-duplicate indices).

So if we're going to be adding new ops anyway, perhaps the best solution would be to add an op that does those sparse updates (the equivalent of `scatter_update`, but for tensors) to cover that use case, and then restrict the definition of `dynamic_stitch` to unique indices to handle the other use cases (without sacrificing performance).

@drasmuss Unfortunately I don't see how to restrict dynamic_stitch without sacrificing performance.  We're also bound by backwards compatibility to keep the current spec, which explicitly allows duplicates and says how they're deduped.

I probably won't have time to add a new kernel, so if anyone else wants to take that on feel free.  In the meantime I squashed all the commits for readability as requested (just keeping implementation 2).  The alternate implementations are preserved at https://github.com/drasmuss/tensorflow/tree/dynamic_stitch_grad_copy if anyone wants to look at them in the future.
Sounds like this isn't going to make it in due to the performance regression, so I'm closing this PR. Thanks for the hard work @drasmuss, we appreciate it. Not everything lands, but such is life.

title: sparse_placeholder failed when specifying shape
body:
When trying to create a sparse placeholder, exception raised if specifying the `shape` parameter:
```
features_placeholder = tf.sparse_placeholder(tf.float32, shape=(16, 20424)) # failed
features_placeholder = tf.sparse_placeholder(tf.float32)  # pass
```
Exception reads like:
```
  File "tf_learn.py", line 92, in run_training
    features_placeholder = tf.sparse_placeholder(tf.float32, shape=(FLAGS.batch_size, etc.FEATURE_SIZE))
  File "C:\local\Anaconda3-4.1.1-Windows-x86_64\envs\tf-py35\lib\site-packages\tensorflow\python\ops\array_ops.py", line 1653, in sparse_placeholder
    shape=shape
  File "C:\local\Anaconda3-4.1.1-Windows-x86_64\envs\tf-py35\lib\site-packages\tensorflow\python\framework\sparse_tensor.py", line 135, in __init__
    shape = ops.convert_to_tensor(shape, name="shape", dtype=dtypes.int64)
  File "C:\local\Anaconda3-4.1.1-Windows-x86_64\envs\tf-py35\lib\site-packages\tensorflow\python\framework\ops.py", line 669, in convert_to_tensor
    ret = conversion_func(value, dtype=dtype, name=name, as_ref=as_ref)
  File "C:\local\Anaconda3-4.1.1-Windows-x86_64\envs\tf-py35\lib\site-packages\tensorflow\python\framework\ops.py", line 583, in _TensorTensorConversionFunction
    % (dtype.name, t.dtype.name, str(t)))
ValueError: Tensor conversion requested dtype int64 for Tensor with dtype int32: 'Tensor("Const:0", shape=(2,), dtype=int32)'

```

Is this a bug?
comments: hm, is shape getting initialized to `tf.float64` value? You can try initializing with `shape=shape`, and create shape ahead of time as a tf.float32 tensorflow constant tensor

@yaroslavvb thanks for the suggestion. I finally settled down on avoiding the `shape` parameter in the `sparse_placeholder` as almost all examples I found did not specify the `shape` parameter for the `sparse_placeholder`. 

I also traced it into the tensorflow python code, and found that the `shape` is converted to a `int64` array, and the `int64` dtype is hard-coded.
@concretevitamin, could you please take a look. it seems we could handle this case better? It's not consistent with shape arguments on dense tensor, I believe.

@liangwang the reason is simply that, the design of `SparseTensor` already hardcodes the associated shape as `tf.int64` [1], so any downstream ops that consume these objects assume likewise as well.

[1] https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/python/framework/sparse_tensor.py#L59
@concretevitamin , yes, it is hard-coded. But would this be considered a bug, since it will fail when specifying shapes with immediate numbers (like the first example I listed in the original post)?
@concretevitamin, ping

I don't consider it a bug in `sparse_palceholder`... There's no automatic type casting in TensorFlow at the moment, which I think is the effect you're asking for.  (If you have a proposed design to solve this general problem, we'd love to hear about it in a focused issue!)

If this is not considered as a bug, then how should we use the shape parameter? Clearly, it will fail by specifying plain numbers. At least, it helps by providing an example if the usage is not straightforward. Maybe, we can add the usage example to the document to avoid any further confusion.

@liangwang you can use `shape` parameter as follows:

`
tf.sparse_placeholder(tf.float32, shape=np.array((16, 20424)))
`

@liangwang what @yaroslavvb said (since `numpy.ndarray` defaults to 64-bit).  Another way could be:

`tf.sparse_placeholder(tf.float32, shape=tf.constant([16, 20424], tf.int64))`
What if I wish to apply functions that manipulate the shape of sparse tensors, like `tf.expand_dims()` and `tf.squeeze()`? It fails even if I have assigned a shape to my `tf.sparse_placeholder`.

title: Feature request: enable modification of data in tfrecord files
body:
It would be nice to be able to append or remove samples to or from an existing set of samples saved in a tfrecords file. Otherwise the file has to be duplicated, which is unpractical for datasets >> 1TB.
Formulated in a more generalized way, this can also be seen as splitting and concatenating tfrecord files.
comments: I suspect that this is a feature that is not practical to implement since TFRecords are a simple serial file format. Additionally, compressed gzip is not seekable, so the compression would  have to be chunked into some seekable block size. Probably, the best solution is to shard your data into multiple record files. @concretevitamin, could you comment?
@jhseu, i know you are giving a talk at the dev summit, but since you are talking about TFRecord in it, I thought you might have additional insight.

Removing records is pretty infeasible without rewriting. I'm not sure we'd want to design the format with that feature, because we're typically optimizing for sequential reads and writes.

Additionally, certain filesystems (e.g., GCS, HDFS) don't allow in-place modifications, so it wouldn't be generally useful.

For uncompressed files, you can concatenate them since there is no per-file header. Beyond that, I don't think we have immediate plans to implement append.  That comment you link to was written before we supported compression, which complicates the implementation of the feature.

> For uncompressed files, you can concatenate them

How should we do this? Simply make another file and concat the files to one? How do we prevent compression?

@evolu8 you should be able concatenate with bash or windows cmd
https://ss64.com/bash/cat.html
https://ss64.com/nt/type.html
And as josh11b mentioned, this will only work for non-compressed files

Any update on this issue?
Thanks.
Any updates? Can I append an existing TFRecord?
Any updates? Can I append an existing TFRecord?

title: Tell fix

title: Fixing FileIO tell()
body: tell() doesn't do a _preread_check() before accessing _read_buf. As a result, if thats the first thing one does it leads to a crash.
